== Overview ==
Shōshichii was first established in {{ill|Taihō|ja|大宝|qq=draft|qq=draft}}元年 (701) as part of the {{ill|Taihō Code|ja|大宝律令|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, along with other Ranks. Under the {{ill|Ritsuryō system|ja|律令制|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Shōshichii was further divided into two subRanks: Upper Shōshichii (正七位上) and Lower Shōshichii (正七位下). During the early {{ill|Meiji period|ja|明治時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the {{ill|Daijōkan system (Meiji period)|ja|太政官制|qq=draft|qq=draft}} abolished these subRanks, and Shōshichii was equivalent to positions such as Assistant Grand Recorder (権大史) in the {{ill|Jingikan|ja|神祇官|1=Department of Divinities|blank= (明治時代)|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and Assistant Junior Recorder (権少史) in the {{ill|Daijōkan|ja|太政官 (明治時代)|qq=draft|qq=draft}}.

Until the suspension of conferring Ranks to living persons in 1946 (Shōwa 21), Shōshichii was the initial Rank for {{ill|Civil officials|ja|文官|qq=draft|qq=draft}} at the {{ill|Kōtōkan|ja|高等官|qq=draft|qq=draft}} 6th grade (e.g., police inspectors) and {{ill|Military officers|ja|武官|qq=draft|qq=draft}} at the Rank of captain (e.g., company commanders). After the suspension, Shōshichii was awarded posthumously, typically to local branch directors of government ministries, police officers at the inspector Rank, and similar positions.

